      Positive and negative finfluence
   =20
 =20
So on the one hand, the state of Massachusetts fined Massachusetts Mutual L=
ife Insurance Co. $4 million for letting Keith Gill do the GameStop thing:M=
r. Gill, known as =E2=80=9CRoaring Kitty=E2=80=9D on YouTube and =E2=80=9CD=
eepF=E2=80=94ingValue=E2=80=9D on Reddit, became an Internet folk hero in J=
anuary, thanks to his prescient bets on GameStop stock. For months leading =
up to the GameStop trading frenzy in January=E2=80=94during which nonprofes=
sional traders sent the company=E2=80=99s shares soaring to a record high=
=E2=80=94Mr. Gill posted videos and messages discussing why he was putting =
large sums of money into the stock. =E2=80=A6At the time, Mr. Gill was regi=
stered as a broker at MML Investors Services LLC, a broker-dealer and inves=
tment adviser whose parent company is MassMutual. His role was director of =
education and wellness, and he was responsible for creating educational mat=
erials used by the company and its client-facing registered agents. ...The =
office of William Galvin, the Secretary of the Commonwealth of Massachusett=
s, opened an inquiry into the matter earlier this year. His office said tha=
t while MML prohibited broker-dealer employees from discussing securities o=
n social media, the company didn=E2=80=99t have =E2=80=9Creasonable policie=
s and procedures in place to detect and monitor=E2=80=9D such activity. At =
one point in mid-January, Mr. Galvin=E2=80=99s office said, two employees i=
ncluding Mr. Gill=E2=80=99s manager were made aware of his social-media act=
ivity. MML didn=E2=80=99t take any immediate action, the regulator said.Her=
e=C2=A0is the consent order, which is very puzzling in that it =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0doesn=E2=80=99t say what Mass Mutual, or Gill, did wrong? The gist of it=
 is:=09Gill worked as =E2=80=9Cdirector of education and wellness=E2=80=9D =
for a Mass Mutual brand called =E2=80=9CIn Good Company,=E2=80=9D okay.=09H=
e did a lot of posting about GameStop Corp. on Reddit, Twitter and YouTube,=
 becoming a huge celebrity during its January rally. Those posts did not us=
e his real name or mention his Mass Mutual affiliation, though his YouTube =
videos did show his face. =E2=80=9CGill ran rampant on his personal social =
media,=E2=80=9D the consent order says, =E2=80=9Cfrequently and extensively=
 posting regarding generic and specific securities.=E2=80=9D=09He also trad=
ed a lot of GameStop stock and options.=09Mass Mutual =E2=80=9Cfailed reaso=
nably to supervise him.=E2=80=9DMass Mutual had policies prohibiting its em=
ployees =E2=80=9Cfrom discussing generic securities and company business on=
 social media,=E2=80=9D and I guess he violated them, but I am just not sur=
e I understand why regulators would care about that. Did Gill mislead anyon=
e? Was he providing unsuitable financial advice in his capacity as a regist=
ered person? Was he =E2=80=9Cmanipulating the value of GameStop stock,=E2=
=80=9D as his boss at In Good Company said in an email quoted by the regula=
tors? I dunno, in a sense, but not I think in an illegal sense. He said he =
liked the stock, and people agreed with him, so the stock went up. Seems fi=
ne, or fine-ish.=C2=A0By the way, surely Keith Gill has done more to teach =
ordinary people about the financial system than every other =E2=80=9Cfinanc=
ial wellness educator=E2=80=9D in the history of the world combined? Like G=
ameStop was=C2=A0very much a teachable moment, in a way that whatever In Go=
od Company was up to probably was not. (Do you=C2=A0know what In Good Compa=
ny was up to?) The guy explained how stock trading works=C2=A0to Congress. =
Ooh, he violated a social-media policy, who cares.=C2=A0On the other hand, =
 what=E2=80=99s all this then:At first no one could explain why business wa=
s picking up at Betterment, a robo adviser aimed at newbie investors. There=
 were about 10,000 signups in one day.=C2=A0Then came the answer: A 25-year=
-old TikToker from Tennessee was posting videos describing how to retire a =
millionaire by using the platform.His name is Austin Hankwitz, and he=E2=80=
=99s managed to land one of the hottest new gigs: full-time =E2=80=9Cfinflu=
encer.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6Once Betterment saw the traction it was getting th=
rough Hankwitz=E2=80=99s posts, it hired him within a month to plug its ser=
vices via social media.Wealthfront, another robo adviser, has partnered wit=
h about 15 influencers including Haley Sacks =E2=80=94 known on Instagram a=
s Mrs. Dow Jones =E2=80=94 according to Kate Wauck, the firm=E2=80=99s chie=
f communications officer.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CQuite frankly, they=E2=80=99re just=
 better at telling our story than we are,=E2=80=9D she said.I =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0okay =E2=80=A6=C2=A0so =E2=80=A6=C2=A0some guy on TikTok is like =E2=80=
=9Cyou=E2=80=99ll be a millionaire if you use Betterment=E2=80=9D and Bette=
rment was like =E2=80=9Coh thanks, nice of you to say, here=E2=80=99s some =
money, keep saying that,=E2=80=9D and he did, and =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Mass Mutua=
l gets in trouble for Keith Gill using Reddit under a pseudonym?I do feel l=
ike there is a=C2=A0traditional old-school view in the financial industry t=
hat if anyone at a regulated firm so much as looks at social media, that=E2=
=80=99s illegal, and the completely unexplained Mass Mutual fine reinforces=
 that belief. And then there is the more modern view of, like, go nuts,=C2=
=A0pay some teens to pitch crypto on TikTok:Smash that like button, Wall St=
reet: The teens and 20-somethings who steer online conversation =E2=80=94 a=
bout life hacks, beauty products, Hollywood blockbusters, you name it =E2=
=80=94 are now blazing their way into finance. Influencers like Hankwitz ca=
n translate concepts like passive investing or tax harvesting into digestib=
le social media videos using playful twists, music and colorful captions, m=
aking investment products and the like feel accessible to millennials and G=
en Z-ers. =E2=80=A6Hankwitz charges anywhere from $4,500 to $8,000 per post=
 on his TikTok page. He said Fundrise, a real estate investment platform, p=
ays him every month to post two videos on his TikTok, and also offers him a=
 monthly bonus of as much as $2,000 based on how many people he pushes to t=
he platform. BlockFi, a cryptocurrency trading platform, offers him $25 per=
 person pushed to the platform through his unique code. And stock trading a=
pp Public.com offered him a monthly retainer and company equity for a contr=
act that includes replacing the Yahoo Finance stock charts on his videos wi=
th theirs.=C2=A0These quotes are all from Misyrlena Egkolfopoulou=E2=80=99s=
 Bloomberg article, titled =E2=80=9CWall Street Influencers Are Making $500=
,000, Topping Even Bankers,=E2=80=9D and I could quote it endlessly:To get =
there, creators have to develop a certain persona =E2=80=94 and on FinTok a=
nd its Instagram counterpart, there=E2=80=99s enough variety for everyone. =
Creators from a variety of ages, backgrounds and ethnicities offer advice a=
bout how to open a Roth IRA, how to invest in real estate, how trading opti=
ons makes more sense if you compare it to buying makeup, or how to use astr=
ology to predict the price of Bitcoin.=C2=A0It is all legal-ish:Betterment=
=E2=80=99s compliance and legal teams perform detailed reviews of their soc=
ial media partners=E2=80=99 scripts. Influencers will then shoot the video =
and send it back to compliance for a second review. Wealthfront said that i=
t does extensive background checks on the influencers that get selected to =
partner with them before signing any contracts. It also includes stipulatio=
ns in the contract that allow Wealthfront to cancel if certain terms are vi=
olated by the creators.=C2=A0The main law that governs financial influencer=
s is the Investment Advisers Act of 1940, which specifies what qualifies as=
 investment advice and who must register with state and federal regulators =
in order to provide it. But there=E2=80=99s one exemption that reduces the =
risk to influencers, according to Joshua Escalante Troesh, a registered fin=
ancial adviser and founder of Purposeful Strategic Partners: Unregistered i=
ndividuals can dispense financial advice if they do so through a =E2=80=9Cp=
ublication of regular and general circulation.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0I suppose that=
=E2=80=99s how Money Stuff gets away with dispensing financial advice, haha=
ha no just kidding=C2=A0nothing here is ever financial advice.=C2=A0Get you=
r financial advice from TikTok!
