money, keep saying that,=E2=80=9D and he did, and =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Mass Mutua=
l gets in trouble for Keith Gill using Reddit under a pseudonym?</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I do feel like there is a=C2=A0traditional old-school=
 view in the financial industry that if anyone at a regulated firm so much =
as looks at social media, that=E2=80=99s illegal, and the completely unexpl=
ained Mass Mutual fine reinforces that belief. And then there is the more m=
odern view of, like, go nuts,=C2=A0pay some teens to pitch crypto on TikTok=
:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Smash that like button, Wall =
Street: The teens and 20-somethings who steer online conversation =E2=80=94=
 about life hacks, beauty products, Hollywood blockbusters, you name it =E2=
=80=94 are now blazing their way into finance. Influencers like Hankwitz ca=
n translate concepts like passive investing or tax harvesting into digestib=
le social media videos using playful twists, music and colorful captions, m=
aking investment products and the like feel accessible to millennials and G=
en Z-ers. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Hankwitz charges anywhe=
re from $4,500 to $8,000 per post on his TikTok page. He said Fundrise, a r=
eal estate investment platform, pays him every month to post two videos on =
his TikTok, and also offers him a monthly bonus of as much as $2,000 based =
on how many people he pushes to the platform. BlockFi, a cryptocurrency tra=
ding platform, offers him $25 per person pushed to the platform through his=
 unique code. And stock trading app Public.com offered him a monthly retain=
er and company equity for a contract that includes replacing the Yahoo Fina=
nce stock charts on his videos with theirs.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These quotes are all from Misyrlena Egkolfopoulou=E2=
=80=99s Bloomberg article, titled =E2=80=9CWall Street Influencers Are Maki=
ng $500,000, Topping Even Bankers,=E2=80=9D and I could quote it endlessly:=
</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To get there, creators have to=
 develop a certain persona =E2=80=94 and on FinTok and its Instagram counte=
rpart, there=E2=80=99s enough variety for everyone. Creators from a variety=
 of ages, backgrounds and ethnicities offer advice about how to open a Roth=
 IRA, how to invest in real estate, how trading options makes more sense if=
 you compare it to buying makeup, or how to use astrology to predict the pr=
ice of Bitcoin.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is al=
l legal-ish:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Betterment=E2=80=
=99s compliance and legal teams perform detailed reviews of their social me=
dia partners=E2=80=99 scripts. Influencers will then shoot the video and se=
nd it back to compliance for a second review. Wealthfront said that it does=
 extensive background checks on the influencers that get selected to partne=
r with them before signing any contracts. It also includes stipulations in =
the contract that allow Wealthfront to cancel if certain terms are violated=
 by the creators.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The main law that g=
overns financial influencers is the Investment Advisers Act of 1940, which =
specifies what qualifies as investment advice and who must register with st=
ate and federal regulators in order to provide it. But there=E2=80=99s one =
exemption that reduces the risk to influencers, according to Joshua Escalan=
te Troesh, a registered financial adviser and founder of Purposeful Strateg=
ic Partners: Unregistered individuals can dispense financial advice if they=
 do so through a =E2=80=9Cpublication of regular and general circulation.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose that=
=E2=80=99s how Money Stuff gets away with dispensing financial advice, haha=
